{"id": "m01", "question": "What is the first-line antibiotic treatment for community-acquired pneumonia in a previously healthy outpatient adult?", "ground_truth": "A macrolide (e.g. azithromycin or clarithromycin) or doxycycline is first-line for previously healthy outpatients with no comorbidities or recent antibiotic use; patients with comorbidities get a respiratory fluoroquinolone or a beta-lactam plus a macrolide.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m02", "question": "What are the core components of managing diabetic ketoacidosis?", "ground_truth": "Management of DKA centers on intravenous fluid resuscitation (isotonic saline), a continuous insulin infusion, and electrolyte correction—especially potassium repletion—with close monitoring of glucose, anion gap, and ketones, plus treatment of the precipitating cause.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m03", "question": "What is a preferred first-line antihypertensive for a patient with comorbid diabetes mellitus?", "ground_truth": "An ACE inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB) is preferred first-line in patients with diabetes, particularly when albuminuria is present, because of renal protective benefits.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
{"id": "m04", "question": "What are the qSOFA criteria used to identify patients at risk of poor outcomes from sepsis?", "ground_truth": "qSOFA flags sepsis risk with any 2 of 3 bedside criteria: respiratory rate >= 22/min, altered mental status (GCS < 15), and systolic blood pressure <= 100 mmHg.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m05", "question": "What is the first-line pharmacologic treatment for status epilepticus?", "ground_truth": "A benzodiazepine (intravenous lorazepam, or intramuscular midazolam if no IV access) is first-line for status epilepticus, followed by a second-line antiseizure agent such as levetiracetam, fosphenytoin/phenytoin, or valproate if seizures persist.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": true}
{"id": "m06", "question": "What are important contraindications to metformin?", "ground_truth": "Metformin is contraindicated in significant renal impairment (e.g. eGFR < 30 mL/min/1.73m2), acute metabolic acidosis including diabetic ketoacidosis, and conditions predisposing to lactic acidosis or tissue hypoperfusion; it is held around iodinated contrast and in acute illness.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
{"id": "m07", "question": "By what mechanism do beta-blockers benefit patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction?", "ground_truth": "Beta-blockers antagonize beta-adrenergic receptors, blunting chronic sympathetic (catecholamine) overactivation; this lowers heart rate and myocardial oxygen demand, reduces arrhythmia risk, and promotes reverse remodeling, improving ejection fraction and survival in HFrEF.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
{"id": "m08", "question": "What is the initial diagnostic workup for a hemodynamically stable patient with suspected pulmonary embolism?", "ground_truth": "Risk stratify with a clinical pretest probability score (e.g. Wells); for low/intermediate probability use a D-dimer, and if elevated or probability is high proceed to CT pulmonary angiography (the test of choice), with a V/Q scan as an alternative when CTPA is contraindicated.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
{"id": "m09", "question": "What is the typical clinical presentation of acute appendicitis?", "ground_truth": "Acute appendicitis typically presents with periumbilical pain that migrates to the right lower quadrant (McBurney point), accompanied by anorexia, nausea/vomiting, low-grade fever, and right lower quadrant tenderness with guarding and rebound.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
{"id": "m10", "question": "What is the mechanism of action of ACE inhibitors?", "ground_truth": "ACE inhibitors block angiotensin-converting enzyme, reducing conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II; this causes vasodilation, lowers aldosterone (reducing sodium/water retention), and decreases bradykinin breakdown, collectively lowering blood pressure and reducing cardiac/renal afterload.", "source": "statpearls", "type": "factual", "smoke": false}
